{Introduction In this course, you will find a repertoire for Black against 1.d4 
based on the Ragozin Defense. The repertoire against the Queen's Gambit is 
completed by our companion course, 'Short & Sweet: The Nimzo-Indian'. While this 
course is designed to get you up and running with the Ragozin in no time at all, 
if you would benefit from more in-depth analysis and coverage you might also 
enjoy our full course Lifetime Repertoires: The Nimzo-Ragozin 
https://www.chessable.com/lifetime-repertoires-the-nimzo-ragozin/course/17354/ 
These openings have been chosen with the purpose of providing a solid, reliable 
defence for Black which can last a lifetime. The Ragozin and Nimzo-Indian are 
top-class openings played at the very highest levels with success. The Ragozin 
is widely-regarded as one of the best defences against 1.d4 - in fact, this 
results in many players preferring Nc3 on move 3 to avoid it. In that case, we 
have you covered with our 'Short & Sweet: The Nimzo-Indian' course. You can try 
that out for free here: 
https://www.chessable.com/short-sweet-the-nimzo-indian/course/27858/ All that's 
left is for us to wish you luck on your journey of learning and playing the 
Ragozin! Good luck and enjoy! Christof and Daniel} 1. -- *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The Ragozin"]
[Site "The Ragozin"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "The Ragozin"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-ragozin/course/27861, variation/5080832"]

1. d4 {[%cal Be2e4][%csl Gd4,Ge4] Together with 1.e4, this is of course White's 
most direct and challenging attempt for an advantage.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4][%csl 
Ge4] Controlling e4 in the most flexible way possible.} 2. c4 {[%cal Gc4d5][%csl 
Gd5] White can't play e4 and get the 'perfect centre', so he settles for 
controlling the centre with the c-pawn instead.} e6 {[%cal Bd7d5,Bf8b4] A very 
flexible move. We prepare to wheel out our bishop to b4, pinning a knight on c3, 
or fight for the centre with ...d5.} 3. Nf3 ({In recent times this has been seen 
as more challenging than 3. Nc3. The Nimzo-Indian, after} 3. Nc3 Bb4 {, is 
rock-solid and White has a near impossible time trying to prove even the 
slightest of edges against it.}) {White's attention has shifted to trying to 
find something after 3. Nf3 instead. The idea behind delaying the knight's 
development to c3 is to avoid the ...Bb4 pin of course. This position is a 
fairly major crossroads. Black can try a number of different, decent openings 
here, each with its own set of plans and ideas: • 1. The Bogo-Indian with 3... 
Bb4+ is typically followed up with play on the dark squares, such as ...Qe7, 
...d6 and ...e5. • 2. The transposition to the Modern Benoni with 3... c5 is 
another option too. Black's point is that by using this move order he has 
avoided some of White's scarier tries after the 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 move order. 
• 3. The Queen's Indian, with 3... b6, is a classic complement to the 
Nimzo-Indian. Black persists with the idea of controlling the centre, especially 
the e4 square, with pieces and not pawns. • 4. The Queen's Gambit Declined, as 
well as the Tarrasch and Semi-Slav can also arise after 3... d5. • 5. However, 
our choice is 3... d5 followed by meeting 4. Nc3 with ...Bb4. This is known as 
the Ragozin, which can be described as a mixture between the solidity of the 
Queen's Gambit Declined and activity of the Nimzo-Indian. The Ragozin also has a 
very nice synergy with the Nimzo-Indian, since many lines can transpose and 
plenty of the ideas and plans are applicable to both.} d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 {The 
starting point of the Ragozin. The Ragozin is named after a strong Soviet 
Grandmaster, Viacheslav Ragozin. In recent years, the Ragozin has picked up in 
popularity significantly and become very fashionable. Much of the world's elite 
play the Ragozin regularly now.} ({Black develops the bishop more actively than 
in the Queen's Gambit Declined - where it goes to e7, but this also has its own 
set of disadvantages. In addition to the QGD, Black could also play} 4... c6 
{with a Semi-Slav,}) (4... c5 {with a Tarrasch}) ({or} 4... dxc4 {which is the 
Vienna.}) {This is the starting position of this course and a major branching 
point. We will look at the following major tries by White: •} (Bb4 5. Qb3 
{attacks Black's bishop and puts pressure on d5. White is trying to force a 
capture on c3 so he can recapture with the queen.}) {•} (Bb4 5. Qa4+ {is 
played with the idea of forcing Black's knight to c6, where it is misplaced 
since it blocks the black c-pawn.}) {•} (Bb4 5. cxd5 {is White's second most 
common move and one of White's critical tries.}) {•} (Bb4 5. Bg5 {is White's 
main move - nothing could be more natural than developing the bishop and 
simultaneously pinning Black's knight.}) {Our plan in this repertoire really 
depends on which of the 4 options above White chooses, however, we do have 2 
general overarching ideas: • 1. We are trying to keep the pawn on d5 as long 
as possible. This means that we only take on c4 when it really suits us 
concretely, such as when White moves his light-squared bishop. • 2. Whenever 
White's bishop appears on g5, we kick it back immediately with ...h6.} *

