[Comment "short-sweet-the-ragozin/course/27861, variation/4744428"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5 {This is white's second most 
common move behind 5. Bg5 and it bears similarity to the Queen's Gambit Declined 
Exchange Variation. Taking on d5 has the advantage of removing the hanging 
c4-pawn, thus preventing any of Black's plans involving ...dxc4, but on the 
other hand it also opens up the c8-h3 diagonal for our light-squared bishop. In 
this chapter we will try to take full advantage of this fact by developing our 
light-squared bishop to f5 (or in a few cases, to g4).} exd5 6. Bf4 {This move 
is quite far behind White's 2 most common moves, but it has had quite a few very 
strong players play it over the last few years. Play in this line does tend to 
become quite unorthodox, so it is important to pay attention to some of these 
lines.} Ne4 {[%cal Ge4c3,Gb4e1][%csl Rc3] By choosing f4 over g5, white hasn't 
pinned our knight, which we can use to our advantage by activating it on e4.} 7. 
Rc1 {[%cal Gc1c3] Natural, protecting c3.} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4,Gc6e5,Bg7g5] It 
might seem quite strange to play ...Nc6 without provocation, but it serves a 
couple of important purposes in this variation. It puts pressure on d4, which 
can be quite important later on, and additionally it covers the e5-square which 
matters since we will be kicking White's dark-squared bishop around with ...g5 
later, and it would otherwise want to go to e5 possibly.} 8. Nd2 {Unpinning the 
knight and hurrying to exchange on e4.} g5 {[%csl Rf4] Chasing the dark-squared 
bishop is thematic in this line, as we've already seen. White has tried 2 
different development schemes here: 9. Be3 with the kingside fianchetto and 9. 
Bg3 followed by e3. We only look at the former here; the latter is considered in 
the Lifetime Repertoires course.} 9. Be3 {With the bishop on e3 instead of g3, 
we will need to continue harassing it with the f-pawn instead of the h-pawn.} 
Nxc3 10. bxc3 Ba3 {[%csl Rc1]} 11. Rb1 f5 $1 {[%cal Bf5f4][%csl Re3] Threatening 
...f4.} 12. g3 Bd6 $11 {[%cal Bf5f4,Bd8f6,Be8g8][%csl Re3] Once again 
threatening ...f4, which white needs to parry. Objectively the position is 
roughly equal, but Black seems to have the initiative.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The Ragozin"]
[Site "The Ragozin"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5.cxd5 with 6.Bg5 Variation 1"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "The Ragozin"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-ragozin/course/27861, variation/4744429"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5 {This is White's second most 
common move behind 5. Bg5 and it bears similarity to the Queen's Gambit Declined 
Exchange Variation. Taking on d5 has the advantage of removing the hanging 
c4-pawn, thus preventing any of Black's plans involving ...dxc4, but on the 
other hand it also opens up the c8-h3 diagonal for our light-squared bishop. In 
this chapter we will try to take full advantage of this fact by developing our 
light-squared bishop to f5 (or in a few cases, to g4).} exd5 6. Bg5 {[%cal 
Gg5d8][%csl Rd5] The obvious choice - pinning Black's knight and putting a bit 
of pressure on d5 indirectly. Black has tried a wide variety of systems and 
moves in this tabiya, but we will be recommend something which has become very 
topical recently since it seems to equalise without too many hassles.} h6 {[%csl 
Rg5] Much like in the previous 5. Bg5 lines, the first step is to force White to 
make a decision with his bishop: will he save time and grab our knight, thus 
giving us the bishop pair, or will he rather retreat to h4 and give us the ...h6 
move for free? 7. Bh4 is slightly more common, but both have been played very 
frequently.} 7. Bxf6 {This is probably a bit less critical than 7. Bh4, and as a 
result it is also a bit less popular. However, this is an important line to know 
since it can be reached easily via 5. Bg5 h6 6 Bxf6 Qxf6 as well. By giving up 
the bishop pair White gets a small lead in development, which he needs to 
exploit in order to try to get an edge. Otherwise, if Black consolidates and 
finishes development he should be at least equal.} Qxf6 8. Qa4+ {[%csl Rb4] This 
has become quite popular with the top players recently and it is second in 
popularity, behind 8. Qb3. It is an important line to know since it is often 
reached via 6. Qa4+. 8. Qa4+ is very logical here, since the knight is a bit 
misplaced on c6. We usually will want to reroute it to e7 later on.} Nc6 {[%cal 
Gc6b4]} 9. e3 {Natural and best.} O-O 10. Be2 ({White wants to avoid the trade 
of light-squared bishops after} 10. Bd3 Bf5 {.}) Be6 {[%cal Bb4d6,Bc6e7,Be7g6] 
Many other moves have been played, which are also decent options. All in all, 
Black shouldn't have too many issues here, as long as he plays with a plan - the 
positions here aren't too forcing.} 11. O-O a6 {[%cal Ga6b5][%csl Gb5] A very 
useful multi-purpose move. It secures the bishops retreat to d6 and also 
prepares a future ...b5.} 12. Rfc1 Bd6 {There's no need to give up the bishop 
pair now, especially with the rook able to recapture on c3.} 13. Qd1 Ne7 {[%cal 
Be7g6] Rerouting the knight to e7 is useful since in many cases it can aid in 
kingside play, but also it gets out of the way of the c-pawn.} 14. Na4 {[%cal 
Ga4c5][%csl Gc5] Heading for c5.} b6 {[%cal Gb6c5][%csl Gc5] Preventing Nc5. 
White has difficulties making progress on the queenside since c7 is basically 
invulnerable.} 15. b4 g5 $11 {[%cal Be7g6,Bg5g4] with good play on the 
kingside.} *

