[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "The Ragozin"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-ragozin/course/27861, variation/4744449"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qb3 {This is quite a bit less common 
than the 3 main moves - 5. Bg5, 5. cxd5 and 5. Qa4+ - we covered in the previous 
lines, but it has picked up in popularity recently, including at the elite 
level, so Black definitely needs to know what to do. Moreover, it is the only 
other independent move (which doesn't transpose into the Nimzo-Indian) which is 
theoretically challenging. White attacks our bishop, while also intending to 
recapture on c3 with his queen. There are a few drawbacks to 5. Qb3, such as 
reduced protection for the d4 pawn and the fact that ...dxc4 can now be played 
with tempo (thus forcing an immediate recapture).} c5 {[%cal Gc5b4,Gc5d4][%csl 
Rd4,Gb4] A nice move, simultaneously protecting our bishop and putting pressure 
on White's centre.} 6. e3 {Quite natural, but not critical at all.} Nc6 {[%cal 
Bc6a5,Ga5b3,Ga5c4][%csl Rb3,Rc4]} (6... O-O {is also perfectly playable, but 
...Nc6 has the extra idea of throwing in ...Na5 on the next move.}) 7. cxd5 exd5 
8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Be2 O-O $11 {[%cal Ba7a6,Bc8g4,Bf8e8,Bd8d6][%csl Rc1] Black has 
a nice IQP position here - White's pieces aren't ideally placed to play against 
the IQP.} *

